\maketitle

\begin{abstract}
Nowadays, various countries worldwide are facing the challenge of renovating a vast amount of aging infrastructure while lacking the necessary capacities and methods to fulfill this task.
In order to assist resolving this problem, the "Global Road Damage Detection Challenge 2020" and a related data set has been proposed in the scope of the IEEE BigData 2020.
In this paper, we discuss two relevant aspects that address this problem from two distinct approaches.
The first section provides an in-depth explanation of our solution to the challenge including details of the proposed methods and the error analysis.
Subsequently, the second part presents major considerations with regard to the practical implementation of such a model to real-life conditions at low cost.
Hence, we propose a methodology aiming at road network maintenance with the purpose of providing a full service integration while optimizing the efficiency and minimizing the cost.

\end{abstract}

\begin{IEEEkeywords}
component, formatting, style, styling, insert
\end{IEEEkeywords}

\section{Introduction}

In the last decade, novel machine and deep learning concepts paved the way to new frontiers in the field of computer vision with tremendous success by pushing its accuracy to a whole new level. 
Nowadays, computers are not just capable of solving simple classification problems with high success rates but have rather achieved the ability to perform tasks of visualization on a much larger scale because they are not constrained by human cognition time conditions.
This evolution in computational perception now allows the proposals of quantitative approaches to overcome certain challenges which have been impossible to solve so far due to the 'human bottleneck', e.g. cognition times, reaction times, etc.
One prominent example of such a task is autonomous driving. 
There, neural networks rapidly process ambient data of the car to assess the surrounding traffic situation and perform certain actions accordingly, leading to a safer overall road traffic.
Apart from the car industry, various economic sectors are still relying on quality assessments of certain processes by visual validation. 
Still, in most cases such visual checks are still performed by humans due to complications in the automatization of these procedures; causing a weak spot in the efficiency of the whole performance.

\
One field of application, where the visual validation of defects is an indispensable component and solely performed by humans, is infrastructure monitoring. 
As a consequence of the economic upswing in the 1960/70s, today's society is confronted with a massive amount of aging infrastructure, such as dilapidated bridges, tunnels and roads, which need to be visually checked frequently.
In 2018, Maeda et al. demonstrated the efficient investigation of road damages in a huge scale project using neural networks with smartphone images of Japanese roads with outstanding results \cite{b10}. 
In a successive project the same group successfully expanded the data acquisition to multiple countries, mainly the  Czech Republic and India, to investigate the generalization of their methods with regard to different circumstances \cite{b11}.
In order to help addressing processes of infrastructural deterioration, they generously proposed their data set to allow other researchers to face the problem using alternative approaches.

\
This paper consists of two distinct parts. 
In the first one, we are presenting our submission to the IEEE Big Data "Global Road Damage Detection Challenge 2020", providing an in-depth analysis of our methods and related errors.
In the scope of this discussion, we elucidate the methodology on improving our model accuracy by taking all kinds of attempts, positive and negative, into account, presenting the main challenges that we have encountered in the framework of this competition.
The second section proposes a possible layout plan of a full service implementation by means of the proposed model to effectively apply the concepts to real life circumstances. 
Hence, key questions and goals like the data acquisition, service architecture, graphical interface, low-cost budget trade-offs, etc. will be covered and evaluated carefully.


\section{Challenge}

\subsection{Dataset}

For this Global Road Damage Detection challenge, we use the dataset which was provided by organizers and split it by a ratio as 0.15 into two parts to training our model. One is the training dataset which include 18123 images and the other is validation dataset including 3156 images. All the images was collected from three countries which was Japen, India, Czech. In most of the images, there were several different ground truth boxs which have been labeled with the road damage classes. In the following part we will show the precision and recall of each class and country seperately.   

