\subsection{Data Acquisition}

\subsubsection{Material and Setup}

Bearing our goal of a modest acquisition cost in mind, the materials and tools, utilized for the prototypical implementation of a service, haven been chosen in accordance to cost-benefit estimates.
As a result, a RaspBerry Pi with 500GB internal data storage was used as a computing platform, controlling a PiCamera HQ camera for the data acquisition, and a GPS receiver XXX-NAME to accurately geo-localize the position at any time.
For reasons of simplicity and practicability, a personal scooter was employed as the driving vehicle whereby the camera was fixed to the front end by means of XXX. 
Each picture was taken with a resolution of XXX by XXX pixels at a recording frame rate of XXX images per second, and taking the maximum speed limit of 40 km/h of the road network into account, at least one photo was taken every XXX meters.
With these specifications, our setup allowed a continuous recording of XXX images during a time window of XXX hours before the capacity of the hard drive reached its limit. 
Furthermore, each of these pictures can be associated to a time stamp which is automatically generated in the moment of its recording. 
From the GPS receiver, a second set of XXX GPS coordinates with correlated time stamps can be obtained. 
To match both sets to each other, a linear interpolation of the image and GPS coordinate time series is performed, and based on a fairly simple calculation, the expected incertitude of XXX m of the image localization can be computed.

\subsubsection{Route planning}

In order to exhaustively and efficiently cover the target road network, the route, taken for imaging, needs to be determined precisely. 
In order to do so, we mapped our local road network as a directed graph $E$ where each crossroad is represented by a node while roads are displayed as directed edges between these nodes. 
Additionally, each edge (road segment) is linked to a corresponding cost, depending on its length.
Following this scheme, our goal of efficiently acquiring an exhaustive and accurate imaging of the road network translates into the following mathematical problem: find a path $(e1,e2)$ in $E$ that minimizes the way while assuring a full coverage of all edges.
This problem definition corresponds to the well-known Chinese postman problem [CITE], which admits a fairly simple solution: finding an Eulerian circuit that covers all edges; however, this is only possible if each node in the graph has an even degree (number of edges connected to a node). 
In order to find the minimum-cost pathway of an directed graph containing nodes with odd degrees, an expansion of additional edges between these nodes of odd degree needs to be introduced where only the combination of edges is considered whose sum is minimal and connect all nodes. 
Following this procedure an Eulerian circuit can be found.

\
We generated the directed graph based on local road network information form Open Street Map [Cite], calculated the minimum-cost pathway and applied the navigation instructions to a smartphone using the OsmAnd application for real-time navigation.
Although this approach allowed for an effective road network navigation, various major difficulties were still encountered. One issue, for example, was the imaging of multi-lane streets. 
Our setup only allowed the imaging of a single lane resulting in an inadequate depiction of some defects because of their displaced position to the camera. 
Another trouble-causing aspect was identified in the navigation scheme itself because it implies a constant driving speed on all roads and intersections, and ignores traffic conditions and traffic signals completely (traffic lights, stop signs, pedestrians, etc.).
Although we were able to compute the optimal pathway with a low-budget (free) solution, and to establish a cost-efficient tracking and imaging setup, we came to the conclusion that the navigation is still a subject of improvement or might better be offloaded to external specialized services.

